ce:section.ce:para:
The UV–vis spectrum in Fig. 1
                         shows that the CDots and C-NIMs exhibit strong optical absorption with their tails extending to the visible region interval in the UV region similarly reported in the literature [37,50]. The specific peak centered at 350 nm for all CNIM samples can be ascribed to the n-π* transition CO bonds [51,52]. Compared to CDot, the absorption value in the UV region decreases in C-NIM1 and C-NIM2, whereas it increases in C-NIM3. Fig. 1 (inset) shows the change in the fluorescence properties of the carbon nanoparticles under UV light (365 nm) after NIM addition. The change of fluorescence color from green to blue (Scheme 2
                        ) is a clear indication of the change in surface properties of CDots by the addition of NIMs, where an increased number of alkyl groups on the CDot surface results in a blueshift [53]. DLS studies showed that bare CDots had a hydrodynamic particle size of CDots was measured as 12.97 ± 1.1 nm with a narrow PDI of 0.23 while NIM bearing CDots (NIM1, NIM2, and NIM3) showed an increased hydrodynamic particle size of 17.21 ± 4.3 nm, 29.03 ± 5.2 nm, and 37.8 ± 5.3 nm, respectively. This increment might be due to an increased number of −CH2- groups dangling on the CDot surface (Fig.1 inside). TEM images represented in Fig. 1b-e clearly showed that the particle core size increases with the NIM tail length, supporting the zeta results given above.
